<TITLE>School principal presents program for Matoaca Woman's Club</TITLE>
<TEXT>
January meeting was held at New Hope Baptist Church CHESTERFIELD — The meeting of the Matoaca Woman’s Club was held on Jan. 17, at New Hope Baptist Church with the president, Peggy Perkinson, presiding. Members opened the meeting by reciting the Pledge of Allegiance. 
 
Attendance was verified by Terry Prior, recording secretary, who also gave devotions regarding grace, love and patience and closed by inviting members to sing “In the Garden” as the opening prayer. 
 
The program for the evening was provided by the Education Department. Wilma Norris introduced the evening s guest speaker, Mary L. Thrift, Matoaca Elementary School principal. Ms. Norris gave a short resume of Ms. Thrift s accomplishments. Among her many achievements, she was the former assistant principal of Ettrick Elementary School, reading specialist at C. E. Curtis Elementary in Chester. 
 
Ms. Thrift spoke about the history and interactions with the school and community and how the Matoaca Woman s Club has played a supporting role by participating with the students at the school. This includes the Jeannie Dyson Outstanding 5th Grader Award, ‘Kind News’ publication, Reading Buddy partners, donations of school supplies and the community Christmas Tree Lighting event. She also spoke about the future growth of the school and the challenges that will be faced in the coming years. She then opened the floor for questions and answers regarding the school. 
 
The club president, Peggy Perkinson, then invited our guest speaker and members to enjoy refreshments that were provided by the hostesses, Brenda Austin and Nancy Pettersen. The theme for the evening was Winter Wonderland. 
 
It was announced by Wilma Norris that nominees are being requested for the Rachel McEwen Scholarship Fund and the Jeannie Dyson Outstanding 5th Grader awards. A Valentine and Easter Card workshop will be conducted this year for distribution to the club’s home bound friends. The Valentine banquet will again be held at Howlett’s Tavern on Feb. 21. 
 
The door prize for the evening was a 50 50 drawing and was won by Nancy Pettersen. 
 
Peggy Perkinson closed the meeting with prayer. 
 
• This club report was submitted by Terry Jean Prior, Matoaca Woman s Club recording secretary.
